## Severity
Trivial
## Dimension
naming
## Location
src/tools/bash/mod.rs:88-94
## Violation
The retain predicate uses `!is_finished || !output_retrieved` which reads as "keep if NOT finished OR NOT retrieved". The intent is "delete if finished AND retrieved" — requires De Morgan in the reader's head every time. Compounds with the boolean names: `is_finished` is reasonable but `output_retrieved` is bare-noun (should be `is_output_drained_after_finish` per CLAUDE.md's binary-naming convention).

Quoted (mod.rs:88-94):
```
        if let Ok(mut shells) = self.shells.lock() {
            // GC sweep: remove finished shells whose output has been retrieved at least once
            shells.retain(|_id, s| {
                let is_finished = s.finished.load(Ordering::SeqCst);
                let output_retrieved = s.output_retrieved_after_finish.load(Ordering::SeqCst);
                !is_finished || !output_retrieved
            });
```
## Mandated refactor
1. Invert the predicate to align with the comment: `shells.retain(|_, s| !s.is_collectable())` where `BackgroundShell::is_collectable(&self) -> bool` returns `self.finished.load(...) && self.output_retrieved_after_finish.load(...)`.
2. Rename `output_retrieved_after_finish` → `was_output_drained_post_exit`.
